'''Konstantinos Manetas''' ({{lang-el|Κωνσταντίνος Μανέτας}}, 1879–1960) was a [[Greece|Greek]] Army officer who rose to the rank of [[Lieutenant General]] and served as Chief of the [[Hellenic Army General Staff]] in 1931. He also served four times in ministerial positions and was elected to [[Hellenic Parliament|parliament]] in 1950.

== Life ==
He was born in [[Tripoli, Greece|Tripoli]] in 1879, the son of the politician [[Panagiotis Manetas]], the elder brother of Lieutenant General [[Theodoros Manetas]] and younger brother of the politician [[Ioannis Manetas]]. 

After finishing school, he enrolled in the [[Hellenic Army Academy]] and graduated on 11 July 1901 as an Infantry Second Lieutenant. He was promoted to Lieutenant in 1908 and Captain in 1911. He fought in the [[Balkan Wars]] of 1912–1913 as company and battalion commander, and was wounded at the [[Battle of Kilkis–Lachanas]]. After the wars he was attached as [[aide de camp]] to the chiefs of the [[French military mission to Greece (1911–1914)|French military mission to Greece]], generals [[Joseph-Paul Eydoux]] and [[Étienne de Villaret]], and was promoted to Major (1914).<ref name="bio">{{cite book | title = Συνοπτική Ιστορία του Γενικού Επιτελείου Στρατού 1901–2001 | trans_title = A Concise History of the Hellenic Army General Staff 1901–2001 | year = 2001 | publisher = Army History Directorate | location = Athens | language = Greek | chapter=Αντιστράτηγος ΜΑΝΕΤΑΣ ΚΩΝΣΤΑΝΤΙΝΟΣ του ΠΑΝΑΓΙΩΤΟΥ, ΑΜ 4908. | page=153 | chapterurl =http://www.sse.gr/files/19.ΜΑΝΕΤΑΣ_ΚΩΝΣΤΑΝΤΙΝΟΣ.pdf }}</ref>

During [[World War I]], he joined the [[Venizelist]] [[Movement of National Defence]] and fought in the [[Macedonian front (World War I)|Macedonian Front]] as commander of the 4th Archipelago Regiment. He was promoted to Lt Colonel on 12 January 1917 and to full Colonel on 13 December 1917. In 1919 Manetas participated in the unsuccessful [[Allied intervention in the Russian Civil War#Southern Russia and Ukraine|Allied intervention in the Ukraine]] as Infantry Commander of the [[13th Infantry Division (Greece)|13th Infantry Division]]. Following the Allied withdrawal, he led the same division as its commander during the early phases of the [[Greco-Turkish War of 1919–1922]]. In 1920, he was promoted to Major General. As a confirmed Venizelist, he was suspended from active duty in November 1920 following the Venizelist electoral defeat.<ref name="bio"/> 

Following the ing the [[Battle of Dumlupinar|disastrous defeat]] of the Greek army in Anatolia by the [[Turkish National Movement|Turkish nationalist forces]] in August 1922 and the subsequent outbreak of a [[11 September 1922 Revolution|military revolt]], he was recalled to active service as commander of the [[7th Infantry Division (Greece)|7th Infantry Division]]. He held the post until August 1923, when he was appointed CO of the [[II Army Corps (Greece)|II Army Corps]] and soon after named Minister for Military Affairs in the [[Stylianos Gonatas]] cabinet, a post he held until January 1924.<ref name="bio"/><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ggk.gov.gr/?p=933 | title = Κυβέρνησις ΣΤΥΛΙΑΝΟΥ ΓΟΝΑΤΑ - Από 14.11.1922 έως 11.1.1924 | publisher=General Secretariat of the Government | language=Greek | accessdate=5 July 2011}}</ref> Manetas was then promoted to Lieutenant General and sent to [[Paris]] as military attaché, and returned in 1925 to re-assume command of II Corps, until 1926, when he was appointed commander of [[I Army Corps (Greece)|I Army Corps]]. He held this post until 1933, with the exception of June–August 1931, when he was appointed Chief of the General Staff.<ref name="bio"/> He served as Transport Minister (and interim Justice Minister for a day) in the interim government of [[Alexandros Othonaios]] in March 1933, formed in response of an abortive [[Venizelist]] coup.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ggk.gov.gr/?p=1000 | title = Κυβέρνησις ΑΛΕΞΑΝΔΡΟΥ ΟΘΩΝΑΙΟΥ - Από 6.3.1933 έως 10.3.1933 | publisher=General Secretariat of the Government | language=Greek | accessdate=5 July 2011}}</ref> He then assumed the post of Inspector of the Infantry in the General Staff, until March 1935 when he was involved in another [[1935 Greek coup d'état attempt|unsuccessful Venizelist coup attempt]]. Following the coup's suppression, he was dismissed from the Army.<ref name="bio"/>

During the [[Axis Occupation of Greece]] in [[World War II]], Manetas was arrested by the Italians and imprisoned in concentration camps in Italy and Germany. He was [[Greek legislative election, 1950|elected]] a Member of the [[Greek Parliament]] in 1950 for Athens, and served as Minister for Supply and Distribution in the [[Nikolaos Plastiras]] cabinet.<ref name="bio"/><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ggk.gov.gr/?p=1109 | title = Κυβέρνησις ΝΙΚΟΛΑΟΥ ΠΛΑΣΤΗΡΑ - Από  15.4.1950 έως  21.8.1950 | publisher=General Secretariat of the Government | language=Greek | accessdate=5 July 2011}}</ref>

Manetas was unmarried, and died in 1960.<ref name="bio"/>

